Perfection! Nice cozy and not crowded seating, classic decors. You can choose 3,4,or 5 course and the waiters are very professional (they are super nice even if you go with the 3 course meal). The dishes are nicely done and actually taste very good, unlike some other fancy places where plating is the only thing that matters.

First time for us at this well known establishment and they did not disappoint. Came here for wife's birthday. Choose 3, 4, or 5 courses from a bevy of options. Or, choose the chef's taster option. Food was great and staff, from servers to host, was great too. Really enjoyed the shrimp /crab risotto and sea bass. Filet of beef was also delicious. Our server prepared a perfect cherry flambe. Would definitely recommend and return.

The most amazing service and the food was delicious!!! I loved celebrating my husbands birthday here and I would definitely go back anytime I'm in San Fran! Love the style of their menu!!!

My friend brought me here for my birthday dinner and wow was it a struggle to get a seat at this place. Our reservation was for 10pm. Luckily, we arrived at 9pm and they stated that they did have a table available. Their menu is quite extensive and they have the options of 3, 4, or 5 courses to choose from. If you want 5 desserts, you're welcome to pick 5 desserts. You want 5 portions of meat? Go for it! My friend and I figured that since it was late and we were starving, we'd go for the 4 course option. Here's what we ordered: Thai seafood curry (5/5), branzino (3/5), quail (5/5), duck (5/5), filet mignon (5/5), cheese platter (3/5), creme brulee sampler (2/5), and chocolate souffle (4/5). One of my personal favorites was the thai seafood curry which was loaded with seafood and the curry really packed a punch. Each item of seafood was cooked perfectly and everything just sang in my mouth. The duck and filet were cooked perfectly. Each was juicy and tender and paired perfectly with its accompaniments. Just stunning. The quail was the most worth while dish. It came with 2 hefty quails and a piece of cornbread. They were cooked beautifully as well and I was absolutely stuffed after just eating one. Dessert was probably one of the weakest points of the night. I'm normally a sucker for creme brulee, but none of the 3 varieties on the plate impressed me. Their sugar shell was way too thick and the creme brulee custards lacked the flavor I was looking for. The souffle was good, but nothing amazing. Honestly, I'd probably skip dessert all together next time. Upon coming here, my friend and I figured, hey, it's fine dining so the portions are going to be small and we're probably going to be hungry after. And since they didn't limit us to one item from each section, we decided to go for the (what we deemed) most "worth while" dishes they had. Needless to say, we were proven very wrong. My friend has a pretty big appetite, but by the time the 3rd course came out, he couldn't even manage to finish half his plate. We had to package the last couple courses after just taking a bite out of each. For a small eater, 3 courses is plenty of food and if you're a big eater, maybe go for 4, but just know that it's still quite filling. Cons: - Skip the desserts as they aren't anything too special - Really hard to get a reservation at a reasonable time unless you book months ahead - Parking is a bit of a beezy, but it's SF... so... to be expected Pros: - They really know food and how to pair things and cook things to perfection - Service was exceptional - Portion sizes were quite large

How excellent of a job they do with the food can't be articulated in a review, but if I had to summarize, the key points would be: 1) there's tremendous variety, as in this place effectively offers a menu from three combined Michelin star restaurants, 2) the dishes are perfect, 3) the service level and ambiance are fantastic. Setting is incredibly romantic and everything here is top notch. They also send you off with delicious cookies.

I brought my mom here for Mother's Day a few months ago. Valet parking was stressful, which is not what I expect when I'm paying for valet parking. We arrived at 3 for a 3:30 pm reservation, and I walked up to the valet desk and asked if it was for valet parking. I was told "yes, but you have to wait ten minutes." Gary Danko is located on a very busy street, and there was no designated area for customers/valet, so we just had to sit in our car and wait, blocking the road. Multiple other Gary Danko patrons had to do this, and there ended up being a four or five car pileup blocking that street, waiting for someone to come park the cars. Prices were reasonable, I felt. There was a set Mother's Day menu (four courses for $106) as well as an a la carte menu. 3 courses for $87, 4 courses for $106, or 5 for $124. And you can choose your x number of courses from ANY category- I got the 5 course and the waiter told me I could pick from any category (appetizers, fish and seafood, meat and game birds, cheese, dessert)- I could have gotten five desserts or five main course dishes if I wanted to! The food was really good, but not exquisite. The lobster was tender and delectable. But most of the food did not blow my mind like I expected it to. For example, I asked for my seared filet of beef medium rare, and it was slightly overcooked. The dishes that our food came on and plating of each dish wasn't very impressive either. These aesthetic touches are not what I would expect from a standard restaurant, but a place like Gary Danko- I was pretty surprised that the dishes weren't stunningly plated and presented. The dining room is nice, but I am not sure it feels like super high end fine dining- it was very noisy in the restaurant. The service is also not what I expected for a Michelin star restaurant - our waiter wasn't consistent - different people kept coming around. Our dishes were plopped in front of us rather unceremoniously. At other Michelin star restaurants, I noticed the plates carefully being placed in a the most aesthetically optimal direction in front of me. And when I was served my filet of beef, my dish was placed in front of me so quickly that the butter on the filet slid right off- and the waiter didn't even say anything even though I saw that he noticed that it happened when I did. The bread they give was nothing special- It was really just typical slices of french bread, and it wasn't even warm :( and the butter they provided was too hard which made it difficult to spread. Again- things like this I would be fine with at a normal restaurant, but I expect better from a Michelin star restaurant with Gary Danko's reputation! Little plate of assorted bite size desserts with the end of the meal was a nice touch. They were all ridiculously delicious. So was the little takeaway item they gave (a pineapple cake-type dessert that they said was for us to eat the next morning :)). Not sure if it was because we came on Mother's Day, but as we were walking out, my mom and I were each given a pink rose and a little box of chocolates. Very adorable and a really nice touch!

GD is definitely worthy of a special event kind of place. I had been here a spattering of times in the past, but this was my partner's first time here for our anniversary, and it did not disappoint. Service, as always was impeccable on every level; every one really tries to make you feel pampered. Against European convention, we started with our cheese course and our server did not make us feel gauche for doing so. It's so impressive when they wheel out that cart and present all the cheeses. They used to cut your selections for you on the floor and I guess they stopped doing that. I'll agree with the others that have commented about the accompanying soft raisin bread....it seems a little incongruous, but very minor point. Secondly, my partner had the risotto and I had the scallops, both were sublime. On the server's recommendation, my partner next had the salmon and I had the filet. I will say that if you're considering the salmon, be aware that the horseradish and mustard combo is very strong and we felt it was overpowering as neither of us could eat it. It's just a personal preference though, so we didn't complain. The filet, however was ridiculously good. We didn't order dessert but they brought us out the little pastry sampler and a complimentary cheesecake for our anniversary, which is always a nice touch. All in all, GD did not disappoint. Yes, it's a little pricey, but for a special occasion, it was well-worth it. You're not just paying for the food -- you're getting the experience and memory of that experience, which is unparalleled.

I don't think I can find all the words to properly provide you an accurate description of just how fabulous Gary Danko is. The decor and food is absolutely lovely and the service is nothing short of remarkable. I've been wanting to try this establishment since I moved here about a year (and a half) ago. Friends and family had told me this would be a great place to dine and they were on point. Reservations are actually hard to get for a proper dinner time and I would recommend doing it at least 3 weeks in advance. Even then - I always had options of 5:30pm or 9pm which always happened to be too early or late for my plans on that day. Finally, the stars aligned one fateful day and the timing worked out for my boyfriend and I to try this place on a 5:30pm reservation in April. We were greeted by the front staff and subsequently what felt like every staff member that would be assisting us that night. They were all sweet, helpful, and welcoming. I really love the way the menu is designed in that they give you a menu of appetizers, entrees, and desserts and you can build your own 3, 4, or 5 course meal for a set price. You can build it pretty much any way you like, 3 entrees and 2 desserts? Be my guest! 4 entrees? Go right ahead! For two people - we did one 3 course ($87), and one 4 course ($106) with some wine recommended by our sommelier and it filled us up. The variety that you have to choose from is just exquisite and we really enjoyed every dish we ordered. Some of my favorites were the seared foie gras (app), seared scallops (entree), seared sea bass (entree), roasted pork tenderloin and belly (my absolute favorite entree) and the trio of creme brulee (dessert). The pork tenderloin and belly were cooked and seasoned beautifully and every bite left me wanting more. It wasn't even my dish - I just kept stealing some from my boyfriend haha The trio of creme brulee was just what we needed to close out our dinner. Vanilla, blueberry, and bourbon were all scrumptious in their own right - my favorite being the bourbon! They also brought out a small dessert platter with some treats for us with our creme brulee. That was really delightful, as were the parting gifts that our server gently placed on our table (at this point I'm like, how did they know how much I love pineapple! my excitement really escaped me there). The restaurant is really close to the waterfront and Ghirardelli Square - if you have an early reservation in the spring/summer like my boyfriend and I did - I would recommend a stroll in that direction after! My boyfriend and I were able to catch the sunset with views of the golden gate bridge by the water. An awesome ending to a great date night :) Thanks for setting such high standard Gary Danko, really really wonderful experience!

Gary Danko is an amazing restaurant! I celebrated my boyfriend's birthday here while we were visiting San Francisco, and we were fortunate enough to be seated in a private booth for just us two! Each table has red roses on it too, which made it quite romantic! Service was beyond impeccable. There were multiple individuals servicing our table, which made the dinner go very smoothly. They cleared our tables quickly, checked in on us multiple times, served us without any lag time, and refilled our waters without having to ask. I got the 4-course menu ($106), and my boyfriend got the 5-course menu ($124). They served us each our plates, but we just shared our meals family style. (0) Thai Soup Amuse Bouche with Lobster It was very hearty, light, and flavorful. I wish they would have listed this as part of their menu because it was amazing, even better than some of their menu items. (1) Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Spring Vegetables, and Beech Mushrooms Most risottos are unbearably heavy and rich, but this was not. It actually reminded me of a thicker congee, so it was comforting to eat. They were also very generous with the shrimp and crab, which I really appreciated. (2) Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, White Asparagus, Leeks, and Lettuce Cream This was the perfect appetizer! The oysters were like little clouds in my mouth because it was just so fluffy and light. But if you're generally not a fan of oysters, I would not recommend it though because it does have a slight "seafoody" taste. (3) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Morel Mushrooms, Edamame, and Tarragon The lobster was perfectly cooked, and the potato purée was a very flavorful "mashed potato." I loved the broth that came with the plate! Portion wise, this is a quite small plate, so just be aware if you're choosing this as an entree. (4) Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts, and Shiitake Mushrooms OMG. This is a MUST ORDER plate. It was the best dish of the night! You are initially served a plate of white rice, and one of the servers then places the seafood around the rice and then pours the coconut Thai curry over the rice and seafood. The flavor is so amazing that I honestly wanted another plate or even two! It's just so light and comforting. All the seafood was perfectly cooked and melted in my mouth. (5) Pan Seared Scallops with English Pea-Mint Purée, Asparagus, Fava Beans, and Beech Mushrooms Scallops were so perfectly cooked! The description also says fava beans, but I think I had lentils with mine. Overall, really solid dish. (6) Soft Shell Crab with Pancetta, Roasted Eggplant, Cucumber and Thai Lime Dressing This was more like two separate dishes placed onto one plate. The soft shell crab was extremely flavorful, and the herb salad on the side was very refreshing. It reminded me of the inside of a Vietnamese spring roll. Portion wise, this is also a small plate, so just be aware. (7) Roasted Quail Stuffed with Mushroom Ragout, Leeks, Quinoa, and Foie Gras with Baby Artichokes and Green Garlic It doesn't say in the description, but it's served with a mini corn bread cake, which I loved! The quail was super adorable and petite. I thought it was pretty great but nothing too special. The quail drumsticks were probably the highlight of this dish. (8) Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive, and Port Glazed Cherries That duck breast was the definition of perfection. It was so well cooked and delicious. If you're not used to gamey meats, then beware that it is a tad more chewy than beef. As for the duck hash and all the sides, I could care less for them. Those were just okay. (9) Trio Creme Brûlée with Assorted Cookies There are 3 creme brûlée: Vanilla Bean, Brandy, and Blueberry Lemongrass. The vanilla is the classic one, and I just thought it was so yummy. The brandy one is a bit too rich and heavy, so I didn't really enjoy it. The blueberry lemongrass one was a beautiful dark purple color, and it was tart in flavor. The assorted cookies were just okay. (Extra) Complimentary Assorted Dessert Plate We received 8 bite-sized desserts that were all different in flavor. There was only one that I didn't enjoy, which was the red jelly one. Otherwise, I would recommend trying all of them because they were delicious. (Extra) Complimentary Birthday Chocolate Mousse Cake This was very sweet of them to bring out for my boyfriend's birthday. If you truly love the flavor of chocolate, then this is the dessert for you. It is not like the grocery market chocolate. It has a more rich, bitter chocolate flavor to it that is amazing on the palate. (Extra) Complimentary Pineapple Cheesecake Muffin/Breakfast Bread I love that they gave us something to bring home, especially since it was so convenient to eat the next morning before a flight. Loved it! Plus the wrapping was super cute!

    11/10/2017

    My friend brought me here for my birthday dinner and wow was it a struggle to get a seat at this place. Our reservation was for 10pm. Luckily, we arrived at 9pm and they stated that they did have a table available. Their menu is quite extensive and they have the options of 3, 4, or 5 courses to choose from. If you want 5 desserts, you're welcome to pick 5 desserts. You want 5 portions of meat? Go for it! My friend and I figured that since it was late and we were starving, we'd go for the 4 course option. Here's what we ordered: Thai seafood curry (5/5), branzino (3/5), quail (5/5), duck (5/5), filet mignon (5/5), cheese platter (3/5), creme brulee sampler (2/5), and chocolate souffle (4/5).

    One of my personal favorites was the thai seafood curry which was loaded with seafood and the curry really packed a punch. Each item of seafood was cooked perfectly and everything just sang in my mouth. The duck and filet were cooked perfectly. Each was juicy and tender and paired perfectly with its accompaniments. Just stunning. The quail was the most worth while dish. It came with 2 hefty quails and a piece of cornbread. They were cooked beautifully as well and I was absolutely stuffed after just eating one.

    Dessert was probably one of the weakest points of the night. I'm normally a sucker for creme brulee, but none of the 3 varieties on the plate impressed me. Their sugar shell was way too thick and the creme brulee custards lacked the flavor I was looking for. The souffle was good, but nothing amazing. Honestly, I'd probably skip dessert all together next time.

    Upon coming here, my friend and I figured, hey, it's fine dining so the portions are going to be small and we're probably going to be hungry after. And since they didn't limit us to one item from each section, we decided to go for the (what we deemed) most "worth while" dishes they had. Needless to say, we were proven very wrong. My friend has a pretty big appetite, but by the time the 3rd course came out, he couldn't even manage to finish half his plate. We had to package the last couple courses after just taking a bite out of each. For a small eater, 3 courses is plenty of food and if you're a big eater, maybe go for 4, but just know that it's still quite filling.

    Cons:
    - Skip the desserts as they aren't anything too special
    - Really hard to get a reservation at a reasonable time unless you book months ahead
    - Parking is a bit of a beezy, but it's SF... so... to be expected

    Pros:
    - They really know food and how to pair things and cook things to perfection
    - Service was exceptional
    - Portion sizes were quite large

    I brought my mom here for Mother's Day a few months ago.

    Valet parking was stressful, which is not what I expect when I'm paying for valet parking.  We arrived at 3 for a 3:30 pm reservation, and I walked up to the valet desk and asked if it was for valet parking.  I was told "yes, but you have to wait ten minutes."  Gary Danko is located on a very busy street, and there was no designated area for customers/valet, so we just had to sit in our car and wait, blocking the road.  Multiple other Gary Danko patrons had to do this, and there ended up being a four or five car pileup blocking that street, waiting for someone to come park the cars.

    Prices were reasonable, I felt.  There was a set Mother's Day menu (four courses for $106) as well as an a la carte menu.  3 courses for $87, 4 courses for $106, or 5 for $124.  And you can choose your x number of courses from ANY category- I got the 5 course and the waiter told me I could pick from any category (appetizers, fish and seafood, meat and game birds, cheese, dessert)- I could have gotten five desserts or five main course dishes if I wanted to!

    The food was really good, but not exquisite.  The lobster was tender and delectable.  But most of the food did not blow my mind like I expected it to.  For example, I asked for my seared filet of beef medium rare, and it was slightly overcooked.  The dishes that our food came on and plating of each dish wasn't very impressive either.  These aesthetic touches are not what I would expect from a standard restaurant, but a place like Gary Danko- I was pretty surprised that the dishes weren't stunningly plated and presented.

    The dining room is nice, but I am not sure it feels like super high end fine dining- it was very noisy in the restaurant.  The service is also not what I expected for a Michelin star restaurant - our waiter wasn't consistent - different people kept coming around.  Our dishes were plopped in front of us rather unceremoniously.  At other Michelin star restaurants, I noticed the plates carefully being placed in a the most aesthetically optimal direction in front of me. And when I was served my filet of beef, my dish was placed in front of me so quickly that the butter on the filet slid right off- and the waiter didn't even say anything even though I saw that he noticed that it happened when I did.

    The bread they give was nothing special- It was really just typical slices of french bread, and it wasn't even warm :( and the butter they provided was too hard which made it difficult to spread.  Again- things like this I would be fine with at a normal restaurant, but I expect better from a Michelin star restaurant with Gary Danko's reputation!

    Little plate of assorted bite size desserts with the end of the meal was a nice touch.  They were all ridiculously delicious. So was the little takeaway item they gave (a pineapple cake-type dessert that they said was for us to eat the next morning :)).

    Not sure if it was because we came on Mother's Day, but as we were walking out, my mom and I were each given a pink rose and a little box of chocolates.  Very adorable and a really nice touch!

    8/20/2018

    GD is definitely worthy of a special event kind of place. I had been here a spattering of times in the past, but this was my partner's first time here for our anniversary, and it did not disappoint. Service, as always was impeccable on every level; every one really tries to make you feel pampered.

    Against European convention, we started with our cheese course and our server did not make us feel gauche for doing so. It's so impressive when they wheel out that cart and present all the cheeses. They used to cut your selections for you on the floor and I guess they stopped doing that. I'll agree with the others that have commented about the accompanying soft raisin bread....it seems a little incongruous, but very minor point. Secondly, my partner had the risotto and I had the scallops, both were sublime. On the server's recommendation, my partner next had the salmon and I had the filet. I will say that if you're considering the salmon, be aware that the horseradish and mustard combo is very strong and we felt it was overpowering as neither of us could eat it. It's just a personal preference though, so we didn't complain. The filet, however was ridiculously good.

    We didn't order dessert but they brought us out the little pastry sampler and a complimentary cheesecake for our anniversary, which is always a nice touch.

    All in all, GD did not disappoint. Yes, it's a little pricey, but for a special occasion, it was well-worth it. You're not just paying for the food -- you're getting the experience and memory of that experience, which is unparalleled.

Reservations are actually hard to get for a proper dinner time and I would recommend doing it at least 3 weeks in advance. Even then - I always had options of 5:30pm or 9pm which always happened to be too early or late for my plans on that day.

    19 photos

    Gary Danko is an amazing restaurant! I celebrated my boyfriend's birthday here while we were visiting San Francisco, and we were fortunate enough to be seated in a private booth for just us two! Each table has red roses on it too, which made it quite romantic!

    Service was beyond impeccable. There were multiple individuals servicing our table, which made the dinner go very smoothly. They cleared our tables quickly, checked in on us multiple times, served us without any lag time, and refilled our waters without having to ask.

    I got the 4-course menu ($106), and my boyfriend got the 5-course menu ($124). They served us each our plates, but we just shared our meals family style.

    (0) Thai Soup Amuse Bouche with Lobster
        It was very hearty, light, and flavorful. I wish they would have listed this as part of their menu because it was amazing, even better than some of their menu items.

    (1) Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Spring Vegetables, and Beech Mushrooms
        Most risottos are unbearably heavy and rich, but this was not. It actually reminded me of a thicker congee, so it was comforting to eat. They were also very generous with the shrimp and crab, which I really appreciated.

    (2) Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, White Asparagus, Leeks, and Lettuce Cream
        This was the perfect appetizer! The oysters were like little clouds in my mouth because it was just so fluffy and light. But if you're generally not a fan of oysters, I would not recommend it though because it does have a slight "seafoody" taste.

    (3) Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Morel Mushrooms, Edamame, and Tarragon
        The lobster was perfectly cooked, and the potato purée was a very flavorful "mashed potato." I loved the broth that came with the plate! Portion wise, this is a quite small plate, so just be aware if you're choosing this as an entree.

    (4) Coconut Thai Curry with Shrimp, Calamari, Lobster, Scallops, Candied Peanuts, and Shiitake Mushrooms
        OMG. This is a MUST ORDER plate. It was the best dish of the night! You are initially served a plate of white rice, and one of the servers then  places the seafood around the rice and then pours the coconut Thai curry over the rice and seafood. The flavor is so amazing that I honestly wanted another plate or even two! It's just so light and comforting. All the seafood was perfectly cooked and melted in my mouth.

    (5) Pan Seared Scallops with English Pea-Mint Purée, Asparagus, Fava Beans, and Beech Mushrooms
        Scallops were so perfectly cooked! The description also says fava beans, but I think I had lentils with mine. Overall, really solid dish.

    (6) Soft Shell Crab with Pancetta, Roasted Eggplant, Cucumber and Thai Lime Dressing
        This was more like two separate dishes placed onto one plate. The soft shell crab was extremely flavorful, and the herb salad on the side was very refreshing. It reminded me of the inside of a Vietnamese spring roll. Portion wise, this is also a small plate, so just be aware.

    (7) Roasted Quail Stuffed with Mushroom Ragout, Leeks, Quinoa, and Foie Gras with Baby Artichokes and Green Garlic
        It doesn't say in the description, but it's served with a mini corn bread cake, which I loved! The quail was super adorable and petite. I thought it was pretty great but nothing too special. The quail drumsticks were probably the highlight of this dish.

    (8) Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Bacon Braised Endive, and Port Glazed Cherries
        That duck breast was the definition of perfection. It was so well cooked and delicious. If you're not used to gamey meats, then beware that it is a tad more chewy than beef. As for the duck hash and all the sides, I could care less for them. Those were just okay.

    (9) Trio Creme Brûlée with Assorted Cookies
        There are 3 creme brûlée: Vanilla Bean, Brandy, and Blueberry Lemongrass. The vanilla is the classic one, and I just thought it was so yummy. The brandy one is a bit too rich and heavy, so I didn't really enjoy it. The blueberry lemongrass one was a beautiful dark purple color, and it was tart in flavor. The assorted cookies were just okay.

    (Extra) Complimentary Assorted Dessert Plate
        We received 8 bite-sized desserts that were all different in flavor. There was only one that I didn't enjoy, which was the red jelly one. Otherwise, I would recommend trying all of them because they were delicious.

    (Extra) Complimentary Birthday Chocolate Mousse Cake
        This was very sweet of them to bring out for my boyfriend's birthday. If you truly love the flavor of chocolate, then this is the dessert for you. It is not like the grocery market chocolate. It has a more rich, bitter chocolate flavor to it that is amazing on the palate.

    (Extra) Complimentary Pineapple Cheesecake Muffin/Breakfast Bread
        I love that they gave us something to bring home, especially since it was so convenient to eat the next morning before a flight. Loved it! Plus the wrapping was super cute!

    See all photos from Angela H. for Gary Danko

    We came here for my birthday dinner and it was both our first time. Our eyes were definitely bigger than our stomachs when we went for the 5 course meal. I got 2 appetizers and 3 entrees and he got an appetizer, 3 entrees, and a dessert to share.

    My menu:
    -foie gras
    -risotto
    -seafood curry
    -stuffed quail
    -duck breast

    His:
    -risotto
    -sea bass
    -steak filet
    -duck breast
    -trio of Creme brûlée

    Our favorite was the foie gras, duck, and risotto. If I could give that foie gras infinite stars, I would. I mean, I'm not even exaggerating, but that was hands down THE MOST AMAZING FOIE EVER! I also love the risotto, but it's very rich and filling.

    The duck and filet were a perfect medium rare.

    I didn't enjoy the quail very much... It was stuffed with quinoa, mushrooms, and foie gras. I didn't really taste the foie, I think it melted in there with everything else.

    The curry was so beautiful and delish. It's full of flavor and they definitely don't skimp on the seafood.

    I was soooooooo stuffed by our 3rd/4th course, so I had some leftovers for the next day.

    The trio of Creme brûlée consisted of vanilla, bourbon, and olive oil flavor.. I know, you're probably thinking olive oil?! But TRUST ME.. That was the only one we finished. It was extremely satisfying and delicious.

    We also left with take home banana Creme cheese bread that was perfect for the next day.

    They also brought out petite fours and a cute birthday chocolate mousse for me.

    The service was exquisite!

    We will definitely be back!!

    4/18/2017

    Small dining area and even smaller bar. I felt a little claustrophobic in the restaurant so make sure you ask for a booth when making your reservation.

    We came early to get cocktails, no where to sit but they have a spot for standing so that was nice. Drinks were very good and the service was even better.

    Husband and I did the 5 course tasting menu each and it was way too much food. I would recommend for a couple for one person to get 5 course and another to get 3 courses. It was nice to try all different kinds of food. The portions were decent size but the seafood dishes are smaller, just FYI. I'm not going into detail everything we ate because that would be insane and you wouldn't care. All the food was absolutely delicious though. We didn't do the wine pairing we just ordered champagne. The service was incredible, almost too good.

    I wouldn't recommend this spot for kids or picky eaters. Take a cab if you can or park far and cab in. Parking is impossible and it's on a hill so for the ladies trying to walk in heels, good luck. I believe they do have valet but I am not positive on that.

    Great spot for anniversaries, birthdays, or special occasions.
